fields.interests: Artificial intelligence, optimisation, evolutionary algorithms, medical imaging, blockchain

fields.title: Learning to be a Snake: Segmenting the Retina
fields.description:
The nerve clusters at the back of the eye are one of the most visible parts of the central nervous system. As such, the eye really does provide a window to the body! _Optical coherence tomography_ (OCT) provides a safe way of imaging the retina, which in turn can be examined for evidence of disease. The retinal nerves are arranged in layers, and the disruption of these layers can provide evidence of systemic diseases such as diabetes, hypertension (coronary disease) and Alzheimers. If computers can be used to accurately delineate the layers, it opens the possibility of monitoring changes over time, and therefore tracking disease progression.

![Benjamin Bannekat](https://octodex.github.com/images/bannekat.png)
 
As OCT images are inherently noisy, accurately reconstructing the layers, or more specifically their boundaries or edges, is a non-trivial problem that has recently been addressed using Deep Learning. Technically, it is referred to as an ill-posed inverse problem. An alternative "traditional" approach to edge detection uses active contour models, or "snakes". These have some benefits, such as being able to tune their properties for anatomical realism. The aim of this project is to use the snake model as an intermediary to constrain the solution space of learning models."

fields.title: Using Computational and AI Techniques to Search for Anomalies on the Bitcoin Blockchain
fields.description:
In 2022 we witnessed the catastrophic collapse of entities in the "crypto" industry, from the collapse (among others) of the _Terra Luna/UST_ stablecoin, to _3 Arrows Capital_, _Voyager_, _Celsius_, _BlockFi_, and perhaps most notably _FTX_ and _Alameda Research_. Investigation of this contagion has uncovered poorly risk-managed, and in some cases allegedly illegal, practices of lending and borrowing between entities. Some examples can be found in the article _[Did FTX commit fraud? If so, was it from the start?](https://www.ledgerinsights.com/did-ftx-commit-fraud-alameda-wire-transfers/)_

Unlike the traditional financial system, transactions on many blockchains including Bitcoin are publicly available and open to a degree of scrutiny. The aim of this project is investigate, with the help of AI techniques where appropriate, the detection of anomalies, irregularities, or unusual patterns on the blockchain. The longer term motivation is the earlier detection of poor practices that could save significant consumer losses.
fields.references: Coins for Bombs: The Predictive Ability of On-Chain Transfers for Terrorist Attacks, Amiram, D. et al, _Journal of Accounting Research_, **60**, 2, 427-466, 2022.

fields.title: Rumour generation and detection using machine learning
fields.description: Millions of people share information on social networks every day, which also allow false information (e.g. rumours) to spread rapidly and mislead users. For instance, rumors affected political decisions, stock market, people's actions during natural disasters, and the safety during accidents/terrorism. Various machine learning (ML) models are proposed for rumour detection, but correctly identifying them is still a challenge. To improve rumour detection, we can support the detection classifier by generating a conflicting data to learn stronger rumour indicative representations, which then can be used to distinguish more challenging rumour data. In this project, student(s) will (1) evaluate the effectiveness of rumour detection techniques using ML, (2) implement rumour generation framework, and finally (3) evaluate the effectiveness of rumour detection used with the rumour generation framework.

fields.title: Discovering dark matter of galaxies with deep learning
fields.description:
Our own Galaxy is dominated by dark matter‚ only 6% of its mass is visible (baryonic) matter such as stars.  It is however unclear 

(i) how the dark matter is spatially distributed within a galaxy and 
(ii) how much dark matter exists in the galaxy. 

In this project, students will try to infer the total mass of dark matter from observational data using convolutional neural networks (CNNs). First, CNNs will be trained using a large number of two-dimensional (2D) images of stellar and gas kinematics of the simulated
galaxies (by supercomputers), because such 2D images can have information on the total masses of galaxies (``supervised learning'' phase). Then the trained CNNs will be applied to real observational data (2D kinematics of gas and stars) of galaxies  to find/quantify the dark matter in the galaxies.  Thus, new AI-based algorithms will be developed for the discovery of dark matter in this project.

fields.title: Deep learning for finding rotating disks in the synthesized images of simulated galaxies.
fields.description: It is a fundamental task in astronomy to classify galaxies into many different categories. However, it is very time-consuming to classify galaxies manually through human eye inspection. In this project, students will try to develop a new convolution neural network (CNN) to classify the synthesized images of galaxies produced by high-resolution computer simulations of galaxies. In particular, students will try to find elliptical galaxies with rotating disks inside their spheroidal components using the two-dimensional (2D) maps of stellar mass densities and kinematics. First, students will use a million of synthesized  2D maps (images)  to train the CNN for an automated classification of elliptical galaxies with inner rotating disks.  Then they will segment the inner disks using the so-called ``U-Net'' . If possible, students will try to apply these CNNs to real observational data to discover rotating disks inside elliptical galaxies.

fields.title: Developing Harmonic Balance Software to Simulate Highly Nonlinear Superconducting Circuits
fields.description: Superconducting circuits like Superconducting Quantum Interference Devices (SQUIDs) have found a range of applications in sensors, quantum communications and quantum computing. These circuits can exhibit strongly nonlinear regimes that might be useful to improve their performance or might lead to a new range of applications, e.g. superconducting clocks. A rod block here is the fact that traditional conventional time domain simulations of these devices are highly inefficient. This project aims to design and implement (frequency domain) Harmonic Balance techniques to improve efficiency of such simulations. This will help to design a new range of devices based on nonlinear superconductors.

fields.title: Intelligent Virtual Human Companions
fields.description: This research aims to develop intelligent virtual human companions that can seemingly integrate our immediate environment and support us in our daily activities. This technology will be enabled by leveraging recent advances in mixed/augmented reality technologies, and by developing innovative artificial intelligence and computer vision algorithms to endow virtual companions with the unique ability to understand their surroundings and people‚Äôs emotions, behaviours, actions and interactions. Unlike robots, they will be low cost, readily deployable and customisable, and will not have any physical limitations or maintenance requirements. They will thus have a wide range of applications from elderly care, healthcare care to educational training.

fields.title: Seizure classification using EEG signals
fields.description: Epilepsy and seizure are two of the most debilitating neurological conditions that affect tens of millions of people globally. Individuals with epilepsy are prone to seizures. The occurrence of seizure is usually unpredictable and it is difficult to get medical help once a seizure occurs.

fields.title: Adaptive moving target defence for dynamic networks
fields.description: Moving target defence (MTD) is a method to continuously shift attack surface to thwart cyber attacks. This differs to traditional defence approaches where vulnerabilities are patched/removed. MTD techniques introduce uncertainly in network configurations, which confuses attackers to carry out a set of attacks that may no longer be valid. The problem we face today is that our networks are also dynamic (e.g. the cloud, SDN, IoT). Such changes also affect the effectiveness of MTD techniques. This project will explore how the security posture affects the effectiveness of MTD techniques in detail, and explore ways to configure MTD techniques to minimise the disruptions caused by dynamic network changes. The goal of this project is to investigate: 1) evaluating the effectiveness of MTD techniques when changes are introduced in the network, 2) measure the effectiveness variant for different types of changes, and 3) develop adaptive MTD technique configuration to minimise the disruptions of its application when dynamic changes are observed in the network.

fields.title: Machine Learning vs. Applied Mathematics
fields.description: Machine learning, and in particular, deep learning techniques, offer immense potential for a variety of tasks. We will consider the problem of time series prediction for deterministic dynamics. In this setting, machine learning is a fancy form of surface fitting  (albeit with a lot of fancy and very clever extensions). Regularisation in machine learning is essentially framed as a problem of statistical inference. Conversely, in applied mathematics, surface fitting is called functional approximation and this can be achieved with one of many sets of basis functions (radial basis functions, or orthogonal bases such as a Fourier Series, for example). Regularisation can be done via information theoretic constructs such as description length. The aim of this project will be to compare these approaches and attempt to learn what each has to offer the other.

fields.title: Improving Bushfire Prediction Technology
fields.description:
Improving UWAs Bushfire Prediction Technology
The Australis bushfire prediction system was developed by researchers in the Department of Computer Science and Software Engineering at UWA and is used to provide fire intelligence for all bushfires in Western Australia. Australis simulates bushfire spread across the landscape using an innovative underlying model, which permits rapid prediction of future fire spread.  As with all simulation models, there is scope to improve the fidelity of the model; to make it better represent bushfire dynamics. And like many software systems, it will benefit from ongoing improvement and refinement. Key project areas are: 1) developing better rate-of-spread RoS models for particular fuel types using satellite (remote sensed) data; and 2) developing a new GUI to allow fire-fighters to run prediction simulations in-the-field, such as in a fire truck.
These R and D areas are significant: The first addresses the need to better understand how bushfires spread in extreme fire conditions, those that put lives most at risk. The aim is to use a) satellite data from extreme fires, b) knowledge of the fuel types, c) weather on the fireground to develop new, more realistic RoS models. Current RoS models were developed experimentally, setting fires and measuring spread rates. These were never conducting in extreme weather (temperature and wind) conditions, for obvious reasons. The need for a more powerful GUI is also important. It will allow UWA‚Äôs Australis technology to be readily accessible by volunteer firefighter brigades and farmers in rural and remote Australia. 
This project will involve working with experienced modellers and software developers, and using Esri GIS technology, Java code and satellite data. 
"

fields.title: Pandemic Modelling Environment
fields.description:
"Development of Pandemic Modelling Environment 
UWA‚Äôs COVID-19 modelling technology has been used to provide guidance on social distancing and vaccination strategies, to both WA Health and Queensland Health. Our COVID-19 model was the first high-resolution COVID-19 model to be developed and applied in Australia, and one of the first world-wide. It uses an individual oriented agent-based modelling method and simulates COVID-19 transmission in models of specific communities, under alternative mitigation strategies. It allows the effectiveness of one strategy, such as vaccinating 80% of the population aged 12 and over, to be compared with another, say 70% of those aged 5 years and above, by simulating virus spread under each scenario. The age-specific infection data generated by the simulation software is then transformed into cases, hospitalisation and deaths (the health burden) using outbreak data from countries experiencing high transmission rates, such as the UK. This quantifies the reduction in hospitalisations and deaths that may be expected by high vaccination rates and/or application of lockdown measures, for example.
This modelling technology is highly sophisticated and currently requires experts to ‚Äúset up‚Äù the simulations and then manipulate the resulting output data to generate epidemic curves or tables, for example. How can the technology be made accessible by staff in any of Australia‚Äôs eight health departments? 
What is needed is user-friendly infrastructure to both input and output large amounts of data. This project‚Äôs aim is to develop an environment which will allow users to determine numbers of cases, hospitalisations and deaths prevented by a particular intervention strategy, thus providing metrics of the effectiveness of such a strategy. Such results allow optimal pandemic response policy to be determined, informed by running virtual outbreaks.
The environment should allow users to intuitively set-up simulation experiments, and do the following: 
1.	select specific intervention to be simulated, such as hard lockdown or 90% vaccination coverage
2.	select underlying variant settings, such as reproduction number
3.	determine how results should be presented
4.	run the model
5.	compare results with a baseline.

fields.title: Game playing AI
fields.description: Games a a great test bed and research environment for artificial intelligence. There is a huge variety of different aspects of AI that maybe investigated through games: reinforcement learning, reasoning about uncertainty, opponent modelling, decision theory, general game playing. This project is an open ended invitation to research develop and test game playing AI  for any game or scenario that interests you.

fields.title: Making Noise in Optical Coherence Tomography
fields.description:
It's been said that "the eye is the window to the body". In fact, examining the retina can give lots of clues about health conditions!

Optical coherence tomography (OCT) is a non-invasive imaging technology that is safe for generating 3-d images of the retina. The ultimate aim is to interpret and monitor health conditions by computer. Unfortunately, like most imaging technologies, it is plagued by 'noise'. Continuing work is underway to learn to remove this noise and correctly assess the images, but this work is in turn hindered by lack of a "gold standard" to assess algorithm performance.

This project seeks to achieve a useful "gold standard" by considering the inverse problem - that is, the addition of realistic noise, optimised against existing images.

fields.title: Creating small world networks via edge addition
fields.description: Small world networks are fascinating and practically useful. Research has been done on turning networks into small world networks by adding extra edges. The problem of adding the smallest number of edges to minimise average path length has been proved NP-hard. However, not much else is known. The aim of the project is to apply metaheuristics (such as evolutionary computing) to the problem of minimising average path length after adding k edges to a network.

fields.title: RNA Probability Distributions
fields.description: Computational tools for predicting RNA structures are widely used. A very common algorithm in the toolkit determines the probability distribution over all configurations for an RNA. It is often assumed that the distributions for different RNAs all look similar. However, this may not be true. The project is to experimentally determine whether the probability distributions are comparable. A deep knowledge of biology is not required for this project, as it is mainly a computational project involving running existing algorithms for RNA prediction on a representative sample of RNAs. However, those with a biological background or interest are encouraged.

fields.title: The Metaphysics of Artificial Intelligence
fields.description: The question of how our thought, perception, memory and creativity contribute to the essence of self, or the notion of sentience have been deeply investigated by philosophers over centuries. Recent advances in artificial intelligence open an avenue for an empirical approach to some of these questions. This project proposes the design of experiments using synthetic universes (like cellular automata, or Conway's game of life) to investigate philosophical aspects of intelligence. An example might be the duality between induction (learning solely from experience) and deduction (having an implicit reasoning framework to deduce causality). Another example might be the characterisation of aesthetic principals as the expression of common features in distributed neural models. This is an open ended project that will combine contemporary AI techniques and philosophical principles to design experiments that may shed some light (or at least a new perspective) on age-old questions.

fields.title: Cracking the Epigenetic Code
fields.description:
Do you want to use your computing skills to help cure cancer? Do you want to be involved in cracking the epigenetic code?

We are looking at genomic and epigenomic data. Our goal is to find patterns that will give us insights into cancer. In particular, we are looking for students willing to apply statistical machine learning and deep learning to these data in search of patterns for unlocking the epigenetic code in cancer patients. A background in biology is helpful but not needed.

fields.title: Pure Algorithms
fields.description: This project is an open invitation to students interested in a project on pure algorithmics. If you love algorithms and data structures for their own sake and want to build a project out of researching them, we can talk to try to develop a project.

fields.title: Early prediction of infrequent failures from multivariate temporal data.
fields.description: In industry, sensors that record information about the assets condition produce large amounts of complex data. In predictive maintenance, such data can be extremely valuable if it can be used to predict the availability of the asset and help decision-makers to optimise the maintenance schedule of the plant. However, to develop robust predictive systems, we need to look at the right data, understand the relationships among the different variables (e.g. vibration and oil temperature) and use tools that allow for synergistic utilisation of such variables. This project aspires to develop computational data-driven algorithms that capture when statistical properties of the sensor data change over time, and how such change is related to an asset failure mode. To achieve that, we will use machine learning techniques and time-series analysis. An example outcome of this project is a predictive model which can give a probabilistic call on whether or not an asset failure will occur in the next week. With such models, we can create tools that maintenance professionals can implement day-to-day to assist with support decisions.

fields.title: Working with machine learning on very unbalanced image data sets
fields.description:
Main Roads WA is interested with working with UWA on a range of computational modelling, visualisation, machine learning, AI and Data Science projects to do with traffic modelling, traffic monitoring and road maintenance. One of the major issue in these projects is working with machine learning on very unbalanced image data sets. These are images of roads in various conditions. The projects will be involved in determining the condition of sections of roads from videos. The dataset is imbalanced as there are very small number of road sections in bad condition 
Industry Partner: Main Road WA

fields.title: Estimating the total masses of dark matter in galaxies with deep learning
fields.description: Dark matter is the major component of the Galaxy: more than 90% of the matter is believed to be ``invisible matter‚Äô‚Äô. In this project, students try to estimate the total amount of this mysterious dark matter within galaxies by applying deep learning to a large amount of data on dark matter from computer simulations of galaxies. More specifically, the simulated spatial distributions and kinematics of star clusters within the outer parts of galaxies will be used to estimate the total masses of dark matter within galaxies through deep learning algorithms: this is a regression problem. First, convolutional neural networks will be constructed to accurately predict the total mass of dark matter in a galaxy.  Then the CNNs will be applied to real observational data to estimate the missing (dark matter) masses of galaxies.

fields.title: Automatic apparent age estimation and gender classification from facial images
fields.description:
Automatic age and gender classification have many applications in marketing and planning of resources at public places. Recently, deep learning has achieved higher accuracy than human observers at estimating the age of a person from a single image. In this project, the student will use deep neural network models to develop an end to end system that performs face detection, age estimation and
gender classification. Existing pre-trained networks will be fine-tuned to achieve higher accuracy on video streamed from a local webcam.
Pre-trained CNN models and dataset for this purpose are available at
https://data.vision.ee.ethz.ch/cvl/rrothe/imdb-wiki/ .

fields.title: Automatic pedestrian detection
fields.description: Automatic pedestrian detection is an important component of autonomous cars and is also useful for city planning. In this project the student will use deep learning to develop an automatic pedestrian detection algorithm. The algorithm should exploit spatio-temporal features from moving camera and moving pedestrian to increase the accuracy of the system. The output of the system should be the locations of all pedestrians visible in image as well as their scales. The results should be displayed as bounding boxes around the pedestrians. The project will use existing benchmark datasets for fine-tuning CNN models and data collection is not a part of this project. Benchmark datasets can be found at  http://www.vision.caltech.edu/Image_Datasets/CaltechPedestrians/

fields.title: Automatic brain tumor segmentation in Magnetic Resonance Images
fields.description: Brain cancer kills more children in Australia than any other disease and about 1750 cases are diagnosed each year [ABS]. Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) gives a volumetric image of the brain to detect and classify the type of brain tumour. Accurate segmentation of the tumour region is important for therapy. This project will use computer vision and machine learning techniques for automatic segmentation of tumour regions in MRI and their classification into one of three tumour types.

fields.title: Deformation estimation due to non-concrete material in concrete structures
fields.description: Concrete is considered a brittle material with high rigidity, with a low loading toughness, compared to other materials. UWA School of Engineering is testing the concrete containing other special materials in structures which may help to improve the characteristics of concrete including toughness and ability to absorb load energy. The pattern of strain developed in concrete under the load is well-known. However, this pattern of strain developed under the load changes when special material is mixed with concrete. In this project, artificial intelligence and data science techniques will be used to estimate the developed strain pattern in the mixed material structure.

fields.title: Evolution of public transport travel patterns
fields.description:
This project is part of a group supported by the PATREC transport research centre.  Students will build the results of previous projects to understand how Perth's public transport network is used.  The project involves developing and testing data mining algorithms and visualization of the results.  The focus will be on new methods for representation and analysis of travel time series for individuals, groups or regions in the network.

Prerequisite skills: Essential: Programming (eg R or Python or Java), knowledge of data mining algorithms.  Desirable (one or more of): Databases, Web programming and visualization (e.g. Javascript, D3, visualization libraries), GIS programming.

fields.title: Intelligent Algorithms for Prognostics and Optimised Sensor Deployment
fields.description: This project will study how to optimize the deployments of sensors when monitoring structures such as water treatment plants, buildings etc.  These sensor systems are designed to support tasks such as prediction and anomaly detection.   They must also minimize deployment costs including energy.  The project is part of a collaboration with the Advanced Water Management Centre of the University of Queensland and several utilities. The project provides the opportunity to work with university and industry partners on a cutting edge green technology.

fields.title: Energy Neutral Sensor Networks  (IoT for context-aware decisions)
fields.description: Context-awareness can improve predictions based on sensor data.  Internet of things (IoT) technologies can be used to gather context data.  This project involves choosing a sensor dataset that can be enriched by context; testing or adapting algorithms for context discovery, context recognition and context-aware prediction; and developing IoT methods to ingest sensor data for context enrichment.
